reflex activation using electromyography (EMG) and (4) muscle elongation, 
extension and flexion velocities using vector TDI. The passive joint angular 
velocity was linearly related to the passive muscle elongation velocity 
(R(2)=0.88). The maximum estimated joint angular velocity corresponding to 
muscle elongation due to tendon tap was less than 8.25 radians/s. This 
preliminary study demonstrates the feasibility of vector TDI for measuring 
longitudinal muscle velocities and indicates that the muscle elongation 
velocities during a clinical tendon tap test are within the normal range of 
values for rapid limb stretch encountered in daily life. With further 
refinement, vector TDI could become a powerful method for quantitative 
evaluation of muscle motion in musculoskeletal disorders.

